  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Scabies prevention and control in drought affected woredas of Amhara Regional state: Mekete and Tach gaint woredas</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Based on the rapid needs assessment conducted by International Medical Corps in October 2015, access to safe water, household food security, and maternal and child malnutrition have deteriorated in the two woredas of Amhara Region namely: Tach Gaint, and Meket. There is a continuous increase in the rates of deteriorating health conditions throughout the entire community. The low land kebeles of Tach Gayint and Meket woredas are affected by water shortage, and low health facilities support to the current epidemics on skin diseases. As result various contagious disease outbreaks were reported in both woredas. The rapid assessment, and the woreda health offices also officially revealed the outbreak of Scabies disease in Tach Gaint and Meket Woreda and the need for urgent response
As per the woreda health office, a total of 25, 555 and 14,000 individuals are affected by scabies in Tach gaint and Meket woreda respectively. United Nations Children&apos;s Fund (UNICEF) in collaboration with the government health sector offices are working on mass scabies treatment in both woredas. International Medical corps will provide support on the existing identified gaps including on prevention, awareness creation on scabies disease, capacity building for health staff, and surveillance.</narrative>
  </description>
